<br>
The  'Liberty' has room to grow into a general type with many uses. In the same way that the WWII Liberty Ships provided a standard design Mauk2's craft could become the core vehicle of many sub types. The key in my mind would be to standardize. <br>
<br>
A Liberty could deliver a 'short' load to LEO and then continue on to the moon or an industrial complex at L5. Imagine the Liberty Ship setting down on the moon and being reconfigured for interplanetary flight.<br>
<br>
While on the Moon it could be fitted with:<br>
<br>
1) An interplanetary flight command and service module<br>
(Hammer head) that simply attaches to a hard docking port and plugs in to the Liberty’s onboard electronics and ships systems, with no modification to the Liberty Ship. This module would also have additional consumables for the extended flight. <br>
<br>
2) A large escape craft with greater endurance and extended life support.<br>
<br>
3) A forward hydrogen tank with 50% of the capacity of the internal tank.<br>
<br>
4) A Mars capable landing craft/ work boat.<br>
<br>
5) A 125 meter long cargo container handling and attachment beam.<br>
<br>
6) 16 fifty ton cargo containers.<br>
<br>
9) A long range high power communications system.<br>
<br>
10) A forward reaction control station<br>
<br>
Once The Liberty Ship is on the moon 4 long retractable arms would stabilize it (like the ones used on the SL-4 soyuz launcher.). Once that is accomplished the previously mentioned fuel tank and modules would be mated to the liberty and then the cargo stacked and secured on top. As long as things remained standard the conversion might take as little as a weeks time. <br>
<br>
Note: I am using the moon as a launch point because it is now believed that there is a great deal of water ice available for conversion to O2 and H2 fuel.<br>
<br>
The Liberty Ship/(hammerhead) orbital transfer vehicle would now stand a bit over 200 meters tall or about as tall of the Trans America tower in San Francisco. After check out and preflight inspections the ship would be ready. The owners cound be kind and take on a small NASA science team hitchhiking to Mars (for a price) and start the countdown. <br>
<br>
The nice thing about a GNCR's is that they can provide either high volume exhaust for high thrust maneuvers or they can be leaned back and deliver a much higher ISP. <br>
<br>
Once the ship is in orbit around Mars the cargo containers would be detached, deorbited, and make a soft landing on their own. <br>
<br>
Note: The Russians deliver light tanks to LZ's in combat conditions with chutes and retrorockets. The retrorockets fire automatically just before thump down so I think this low tec method would work just fine.  <br>
<br>
<br>
If necessary The Liberty ship could then detach from the extra fuel tank and cargo pallet and park the stuff for later use or crash those items into a designated point on the Martian surface to start building up a nice scrap metal trade. <br>
<br>
With the details taken care of the Liberty could then land on Mars to take on reaction mass. While the beast is taking on fuel the crew could take some R &amp; R and wallow in the Martian Gravity for health reasons before heading back to Earth, Luna or L5. <br>
<br>
The local yokels might take a few weeks to assemble and stack a return cargo on top of the Liberty so the order of the day would be Martian Moonshine and a week at the Olympus mons casino and 'relaxation' facility.<br>
<br>
With this type of beast you could leave whenever you wanted to because of its 7 high performance GCNR's and ample fuel supply. It could hit the direct high-energy transfer orbits and leave the slow lane for NASA.<br>
 <br>
NukePulse.<br>
<br>
Note: Good job on the LibertyShip Mauk2 its a winner.<br>
<br>
<br>
