<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Note: Good job on the LibertyShip Mauk2 its a winner. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
LOL!  Well, I see NukePulse has passed the paradigm shift.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Yes, the Liberty Ship is indeed the enabler for all KINDS of things.  As I have said, once you get out of the cradle, with the kind of capability the Liberty Ship enables, it is like the Solar System just falls open before you.<br>
<br>
As for your modifications:  Sure!  All that would work!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Actually, you have jumped the gun a trifle, I have already envisioned a large degree of flexibility for the Liberty Ship.  <br>
<br>
For example, the central engine would have no gimbaling capabilities.  This serves two purposes: First, it means a common mode failure causing a hard-over condition will always leave you with at least one thruster operational, and for most of the flight path, one is enough.  Second, it greatly simplifies the mounting and plumbing for that engine, meaning that it can be made removable!  <br>
<br>
So, if you are planning to go to Mars, you launch your Liberty Ship at reduced launch weight (a mere 800,000 cargo pounds to LEO) using only 6 standard thrusters, and you replace the center engine with a low-thrust, high Isp model.  <br>
<br>
I could see 5100 seconds of Isp, with a thrust of 100,000 pounds, for that specialized center engine.  It would also be optimized for much longer run-times.  That engine is the one you use for the long hauls, for better fuel economy.<br>
<br>
If the long-haul engine dies on you, you simply dump your cargo to get your fuel mass fraction up, and limp home on one of your 6 standard thrusters.  (Safety, redundancy, simplicity.)<br>
<br>
As for your vision of the trip to Mars, yes, that would work fine.  To get that much mass to Mars in a timely trip, you would probably want to use the special high Isp engine I mentioned above, but it would be doable on slower transits with the box-stock Liberty.<br>
<br>
Oh, a couple of nitpicks:  The &quot;hammerhead&quot; idea looks great, but it would not be a smart thing.  Hanging off to one side like that, the &quot;hammerhead&quot; module would be directly exposed to the neutron output of three thrusters.  If you have to light all your engines for an emergency manuever, you would cook your crew, a lot.  Plus, hanging out to the side like that means you are losing some of the benefits of the hydrogen fuel as a radiation shield. If you need a larger crew space for the interplanetary version, simply add a second crew deck right above the standard one.<br>
<br>
(By the way, the &quot;secondary&quot; fuel tank mounted directly above the crew quarters is perfect.  That way, the crew deck gets the maximum shielding for the long trip to Mars and back.)<br>
<br>
Also, the reaction module up at the nose is a nice touch, but in all honesty, probably not needed.  Save that mass for more cargo.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
That said, your picture ROCKS!!!!  I wish I had HALF the talent you display. <br>
<br>
<br>
Once I have worked on the neutron leakage from the gas core a bit more, I will detail some simple variants on the Liberty Ship, and the missions for them.<br>
<br>
One of the first ones is an asteroid mining variant.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
The one after that is an asteroid capture variant!  <br>
