<br>
NTR's got a LOT of development work in the famous NERVA/Rover tests.  Those are all solid core designs.<br>
<br>
The actual vortex of a gas core design, along with the silica based lightbulb concept, was tested in the late 60's.  The vortex of buffer gas was generated, UF gas was fed into it, and the assembly was made to go critical and produce power.  High temps were reached, and the concept of radiative cooling was proven to be feasible.<br>
<br>
No GCNR was ever constructed as a 'full up' structure, but most if not all of the work done in the Rover/NERVA programs could be migrated.<br>
<br>
In the years since, computing power has progressed to the point where it is now possible to do extensive modeling of gas core designs, using the experimental data from those early, ballsy experiments as the verification data.<br>
<br>
I also suspect that much if not all of the modeling used for nuclear weapons research would have a role in making this concept work.<br>
<br>
So, to answer your first question, Yes, and No.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I strongly suspect that more work has been done on GCNR's that was done on Orion.  Just to put the maturity of the two systems into contrast.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   (Of course, a lot of the Orion work is still secret, but I offset that by the fact that a lot of the applicable weapons research useful for a GCNR is also still secret.)<br>
<br>
To answer your second question, I really think that I have!  The Liberty Ship is an ambitious design, have no doubt, but the principals of radiative, regenerative, and occlusive cooling, combined with short run-times, offsets the very high power levels needed for high thrust combined with high thrust-to-weight levels, while achieving moderate to high Isp figures.<br>
<br>
Remember, the standard Liberty Ship thruster is a very specialized design, only meant for short, savage bursts of activity.  In that niche, I think it is a very doable engineering problem, especially as the more I look at it, the more work I find which is perfectly applicable to this problem.  <br>
<br>
And as NukePulse realized above, once we shatter the bottleneck of reaching orbit, the sky is the limit.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
