er reading it on the nuclear space front page I then went into the message boards and read all the past postings I could find, to see more details of your design.  I love the boldness of it, even if I’m not sure of either the physical or political feasibility of it.  There were a few things that I have questions about but there was one point in particular that I wanted to mention.<br>
<br>
The absorption of the bulb has been mentioned a lot, and one point that you seemed to miss from one of yales early comments, was that you have to worry about the emmission at more than just the extremely short wavelengths.  A plasma heated to 25000 or 30000 degrees will still emit a substantial amount of energy in the infrared, even though the peak emission, will be in the range from 90 to 120 nm for that temp range.  I looked up some sample transmission curves for fused silica, and that nasty absorption feature around 2.5 to 3 microns, is not trivial.  I think the total amount of energy emitted in that range will probably be between 10 and 20 MW/m^2, and with most of that being absorbed, that number is likely to exceed the amount you were worried about from the UV part of the spectrum.  There are also the absorption features at about 1.4 and 2.2 um that may cause problems.<br>
Also the energy from about 20 to 80 nm is also not trivial, and in this region the absorption is high enough that this could add from 10's of MW/m^2 to possibly a gigawatt if most of it is absorbed, which from at least the curves I saw seemed likely.<br>
<br>
Another Also<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> , is that, with the peak radiated energy around 100nm, this is well below the 190 that you mentioned and is also in the region of high absorption for the materials I looked at.<br>
<br>
  I’m curious if you had addressed this issue already or it could be that my calculations are incorrect <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> , although I doubt it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  Or hopefully the curves I saw were out of date, or they were for materials other than what you had in mind.<br>
<br>
I wasn’t sure where to post this, as there doesn’t seem to be a current thread for liberty ship discussion. <br>
<br>
